---
description: FastAPI backend rules for SalesIQ
globs: backend/**, app/**.py
---

Backend stack:
- Python 3.12+
- FastAPI (async)
- SQLAlchemy 2.0 (async) + Alembic (migrations)
- PostgreSQL 16 (primary data store)
- Redis 7 (caching, session, real-time pub/sub, Celery broker)
- Celery (async task queue for transcription, analysis, prediction, notifications)
- OpenAI Python SDK (GPT-4o for analysis/prediction/guidance, Whisper for STT)
- Twilio Python SDK (Voice, Media Streams, recording)
- boto3 (AWS S3 for call recordings and exports)
- python-socketio (Socket.IO server for real-time frontend updates)
- Pydantic v2 (validation and schemas)

Backend rules:
- Use clean architecture. Routes → Services → (Repositories / ORM sessions).
- Routes/controllers must only handle HTTP/WebSocket concerns (request parsing, response shaping, dependency injection).
- Business logic must live in services (`app/services/`).
- AI logic must live in `app/ai/` — openai_client, pipeline, prompts.
- Real-time logic must live in `app/realtime/` — socket_manager, call_stream_handler, event_publisher.
- Async task logic must live in `app/tasks/` — Celery workers.
- Validation must be done using Pydantic v2 schemas (`app/schemas/`).
- Use dependency injection patterns: DB session, current user, tenant context (see `app/dependencies.py`).
- Use async I/O everywhere — all DB queries, OpenAI calls, Twilio calls, S3 operations.
- Use pagination for all list endpoints (`app/utils/pagination.py`).
- Use consistent response models from `app/schemas/common.py`.
- Use centralized exception handling (`app/core/exceptions.py`).
- Enforce tenant isolation at every query: always filter by `tenant_id`.

API conventions:
- Follow RESTful naming; version APIs at `/api/v1/`.
- Use proper HTTP status codes; return predictable response structure.
- Do not leak internal stack traces or raw database errors to clients.
- Use correlation IDs in all log entries.
- Support WebSocket endpoints for real-time call streaming and Socket.IO events.

Preferred backend structure (already established — extend, don't restructure):
- `app/api/v1/`          — HTTP + WebSocket route handlers
- `app/api/dependencies/` — Shared DI (db session, current user, tenant)
- `app/services/`        — Business logic (auth, leads, calls, analysis, prediction, guidance, notifications, webhooks)
- `app/ai/`              — AI pipeline (openai_client, pipeline, prompts/)
- `app/realtime/`        — Socket.IO server, Twilio Media Streams handler, Redis bridge
- `app/tasks/`           — Celery tasks (transcription, analysis, prediction, notifications)
- `app/models/`          — SQLAlchemy ORM models
- `app/schemas/`         — Pydantic request/response schemas
- `app/core/`            — Config, security, permissions, exceptions, middleware, database
- `app/utils/`           — Pagination, audio helpers

Coding expectations:
- Add type hints to all function signatures.
- Add docstrings for non-trivial service methods.
- Keep routes thin and declarative — no business logic in route files.
- Keep service methods focused and independently testable.
- Reuse existing utilities before creating new ones.
- All DB queries must go through SQLAlchemy async sessions from `app/core/database.py`.

Do not:
- Put SQL or ORM-heavy logic inside route files.
- Put business logic inside Pydantic schemas.
- Centralize all env vars in `app/config.py` — do not scatter env reads across files.
- Mix AI pipeline logic with HTTP route logic.
- Mix Celery task definitions with service business logic.
- Hardcode Twilio credentials, OpenAI keys, AWS secrets, or JWT secrets — use `app/config.py`.
